        <h2>The Constitutional Court Ruling — 2018</h2>
        <p>The legal shift began in September 2018 when the Constitutional Court of South Africa handed down a landmark judgment in the case of <em>Minister of Justice and Constitutional Development and Others v Prince</em>. The court found that criminalising private adult cannabis use was an unjustifiable infringement on the right to privacy.</p>
        <p>The ruling confirmed that adults have the right to use, possess and cultivate cannabis privately for personal consumption. This was a significant step — but it was not the end of the legal journey.</p>

        <h2>The Cannabis for Private Purposes Act, 2024</h2>
        <p>Building on the Constitutional Court ruling, the Cannabis for Private Purposes Act was signed into law in 2024. This legislation formally decriminalised private adult cannabis use and cultivation in South Africa.</p>
        <p>Under this Act, adults may:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Use cannabis privately for personal consumption</li>
          <li>Possess cannabis in a private space</li>
          <li>Cultivate cannabis plants privately for personal use</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>What the Law Does Not Permit</h2>
        <p>Decriminalisation is not the same as full legalisation. Several important restrictions remain in place:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong style="color:white;">Public use</strong> of cannabis remains an offence under South African law. Always use in private.</li>
          <li><strong style="color:white;">Sale and supply</strong> of cannabis remains regulated. The commercial cannabis market is still subject to licensing requirements.</li>
          <li><strong style="color:white;">Use by minors</strong> is strictly prohibited. Cannabis is for adults 18 and older only.</li>
          <li><strong style="color:white;">Driving</strong> under the influence of cannabis is illegal and carries serious consequences.</li>
          <li><strong style="color:white;">Use in the presence of children</strong> may have legal implications beyond just the cannabis laws.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Where Mount Kush Fits In</h2>
        <p>Mount Kush operates as a cannabis lifestyle store, selling accessories, lifestyle gear, and merchandise to consenting adults in compliance with applicable South African law. We are committed to operating within the legal framework and to supporting our customers in doing the same.</p>
        <p>We are also proud to be a <a href="/section-21-approval">Section 21 approved collection point</a> — a designation that reflects our commitment to compliance and responsible operation.</p>

        <h2>Your Responsibility as an Adult Consumer</h2>
        <p>Understanding your rights also means understanding your responsibilities. The legal protections that apply to private adult use come with an expectation of responsible behaviour:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Keep cannabis out of reach of children and minors at all times.</li>
          <li>Never use cannabis before driving or operating machinery.</li>
          <li>Use only in private — not in public spaces, workplaces, or shared areas where others have not consented.</li>
          <li>Be aware that employers may still have policies regarding cannabis use, even outside working hours.</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="warning-box">
          <strong style="color:white;">Reminder:</strong> Cannabis law in South Africa is still evolving. Regulations around commercial cannabis, public use, and employment are subject to change. Stay informed through credible sources.
        </div>

        <h2>Where to Learn More</h2>
        <p>For up-to-date legal information on cannabis in South Africa, refer to official government publications and reputable legal commentary. The Department of Justice and the South African Law Reform Commission publish relevant materials online.</p>

